<body>
<h3>UPPER LIMB &amp; NECK EXAMINATION (Whiplash Injury Scenario)</h3>
<div class="video-container"> <iframe allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/p4GHGCM_aiM" title="Comprehensive Upper Limb &amp; Neck Examination Guide | PLAB2/UKMLA"></iframe>
</div>
<p><em>Scenario: Patient (Samra, 23) presented after RTA (hit from behind at
        traffic signal) with neck pain that started a few hours after the
        accident. Task: Talk to patient, assess, discuss management.</em></p>
<h4>I. HISTORY TAKING (Key Points from Transcript)</h4>
<ol>
<li><strong>Presenting Complaint:</strong> Neck Pain
        <ul>
<li><strong>Socrates for Pain:</strong>
<ul>
<li><strong>S</strong>ite: Neck area (patient may point).</li>
<li><strong>O</strong>nset: A few hours *after* the RTA
                (suggestive of whiplash rather than immediate fracture).</li>
<li><strong>C</strong>haracter: Dull pain.</li>
<li><strong>R</strong>adiation: Patient reports no radiation.</li>
<li><strong>A</strong>ssociated Symptoms: Possible neck stiffness.</li>
<li><strong>T</strong>iming: Started this morning after last
                night's accident.</li>
<li><strong>E</strong>xacerbating/Relieving: (To be explored)</li>
<li><strong>S</strong>everity: e.g., 5/10.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Mechanism of Injury:</strong>
<ul>
<li>Car stationary at traffic signal, hit from the back. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=152s">2:32</a>)</li>
<li>Leads to typical whiplash movement (forward then backward). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=183s">3:03</a>)</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Initial Instruction to Patient:</strong>
<ul>
<li>"Please <strong>don't move your head and neck</strong> until
            we've assessed further." (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=224s">3:44</a>) <em>(Crucial if cervical fracture not
              yet ruled out).</em></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Other RTA Related Questions:</strong>
<ul>
<li>Any other trauma or injuries from the accident? (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=283s">4:43</a>)</li>
<li>Nausea, vomiting? (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=287s">4:47</a>)</li>
<li>Headache? (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=289s">4:49</a>)</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Upper Limb Neurological Screening Questions (History):</strong>
<ul>
<li>Any numbness or tingling in the arms/upper limbs? (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=301s">5:01</a>) - Patient says No.</li>
<li>Any problems with power in the arms? Able to lift things properly?
            (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=309s">5:09</a>)
            - Patient says Yes, able.</li>
<li><em>(Rationale: If history is negative, full Upper Limb Neuro exam
              might be expedited or focused if time is short).</em></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Past Medical History:</strong>
<ul>
<li>Any previous neck problems?</li>
<li>Any previous surgeries (especially neck/spine)? (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=362s">6:02</a>)</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Lifestyle History:</strong>
<ul>
<li>Smoking, alcohol, diet, physical activity - <em>Generally skip in
              this acute trauma scenario to save time.</em> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=372s">6:12</a>)</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>
<li><strong>Upper Limb Examination:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=472s">7:52</a>)
      <ul>
<li><strong>Inspection:</strong> Quickly from front and back (scars,
          swelling, wasting, asymmetry). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=483s">8:03</a>)</li>
<li><strong>Palpation:</strong> Temperature, tenderness, pulses,
          capillary refill time - <em>May be expedited or skipped if time is
            very limited &amp; history suggests no UL issue.</em> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=39s">0:39</a>, <a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=508s">8:28</a>)</li>
<li><strong>Neurological Examination (Upper Limb):</strong>
<ul>
<li><em>Rationale for skipping/focusing: History questions about
                numbness/tingling and power were negative. Examiner might state
                findings are normal to save time.</em> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=516s">8:36</a>, <a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=501s">8:21</a>)</li>
<li>If proceeding:
              <ul>
<li>Sensory: Fine touch, pain, vibration, proprioception (joint
                  position sense). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=58s">0:58</a>)</li>
<li>Motor: Bulk, Tone, Power (shoulder, elbow, wrist, fingers),
                  Reflexes. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=66s">1:06</a>)</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><em>Likely finding if examiner prompts: "Upper limb examination
                is normal."</em> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=509s">8:29</a>)</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<h4>II. EXAMINATION (Neck &amp; Upper Limb)</h4>
<div class="video-container"> <iframe allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="864" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/sEhVgHRObQ4" title="Upper limb exam by Dr Ankur #GotAspirEd" width="1520"> </iframe> </div>
<p><em>Preparation: Cotton wool, neuropin, reflex hammer, 128Hz tuning fork
        (though sensory/reflexes may be expedited based on history).</em> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p4GHGCM_aiM&amp;t=26s">0:26</a>)</p>
<h3>UPPER LIMB EXAMINATION (Whiplash/Brachial Plexus Context)</h3>
<h4>INSPECTION</h4>
